WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:05.928 --> 00:00:08.398
[APPLAUSE]

00:00:11.477 --> 00:00:12.560
GELONG THUBTEN: Thank you.

00:00:12.560 --> 00:00:14.520
Thank you.

00:00:14.520 --> 00:00:22.710
So I'd like to start by talking
about the concept of freedom.

00:00:22.710 --> 00:00:26.550
I think the term "freedom,"
the concept of freedom,

00:00:26.550 --> 00:00:29.200
is something that is
very important to us.

00:00:29.200 --> 00:00:33.540
We're very passionate in
our search for freedom

00:00:33.540 --> 00:00:39.090
and in our defense of
our rights of freedom.

00:00:39.090 --> 00:00:42.150
And we fought very hard for many
centuries to achieve a certain

00:00:42.150 --> 00:00:45.540
level of freedom, which in
many ways has been achieved,

00:00:45.540 --> 00:00:48.379
in many ways hasn't.

00:00:48.379 --> 00:00:49.920
But what I'm interested
in addressing

00:00:49.920 --> 00:00:52.050
is the fact that even
though we may have

00:00:52.050 --> 00:00:56.580
a certain degree of external
freedom in terms of how we live

00:00:56.580 --> 00:01:02.850
our lives, in terms of how
we dress, what we believe in,

00:01:02.850 --> 00:01:05.970
what we do with
our time, there's

00:01:05.970 --> 00:01:08.940
a deeper aspect
to freedom that I

00:01:08.940 --> 00:01:15.300
think is more important, which
is deep down in our minds,

00:01:15.300 --> 00:01:18.450
how free are we.

00:01:18.450 --> 00:01:24.400
So if we look at our mind
and we see how often it does

00:01:24.400 --> 00:01:27.200
things we don't want it to do--

00:01:27.200 --> 00:01:30.800
often, our mind goes to places
we don't want it to go--

00:01:30.800 --> 00:01:35.370
thoughts, emotions,
memories, worries.

00:01:35.370 --> 00:01:40.360
So the mind is not behaving
in a way we want it to behave.

00:01:40.360 --> 00:01:41.860
And also, the opposite--

00:01:41.860 --> 00:01:46.780
very often, our mind does
things or goes to places

00:01:46.780 --> 00:01:49.180
we don't want it to go to--

00:01:49.180 --> 00:01:58.140
worries, obsessive planning,
painful memories, reactions.

00:01:58.140 --> 00:02:02.100
When we're sitting in
a car stuck in traffic,

00:02:02.100 --> 00:02:04.580
and then we find ourselves
reacting negatively--

00:02:04.580 --> 00:02:08.180
feeling impatient,
feeling upset--

00:02:08.180 --> 00:02:10.360
this is beyond our
intellect, isn't it?

00:02:10.360 --> 00:02:13.640
We don't plan that reaction.

00:02:13.640 --> 00:02:16.732
Or when somebody says something
to us that we don't like,

00:02:16.732 --> 00:02:19.980
and we feel hurt, we feel upset.

00:02:19.980 --> 00:02:23.690
We don't plan the reaction.

00:02:23.690 --> 00:02:29.470
So in many ways, we are not
in control of our minds.

00:02:29.470 --> 00:02:31.510
And of course, you discover
this really strongly

00:02:31.510 --> 00:02:33.400
when you try to meditate.

00:02:33.400 --> 00:02:37.360
Anybody who meditates discovers
within five minutes, or five

00:02:37.360 --> 00:02:40.420
seconds, the lack of control.

00:02:40.420 --> 00:02:42.940
We're trying to sit there
and focus on our breathing,

00:02:42.940 --> 00:02:44.040
for example.

00:02:44.040 --> 00:02:49.150
And within seconds, the mind
is planning menus, or writing

00:02:49.150 --> 00:02:52.310
emails, or plotting revenge.

00:02:52.310 --> 00:02:55.090
I don't know.

00:02:55.090 --> 00:02:59.020
The mind is going to
places constantly.

00:02:59.020 --> 00:03:05.160
So there's this lack of
freedom, this lack of choice.

00:03:05.160 --> 00:03:06.740
And then when it
comes to happiness,

00:03:06.740 --> 00:03:09.870
the same thing seems
to be the case--

00:03:09.870 --> 00:03:14.480
that we don't know how
to choose happiness.

00:03:14.480 --> 00:03:16.070
It's almost as if
we have to hope

00:03:16.070 --> 00:03:18.680
that happiness will choose us.

00:03:18.680 --> 00:03:21.170
You know what I mean?

00:03:21.170 --> 00:03:24.800
And also, our
quest for happiness

00:03:24.800 --> 00:03:27.810
is very much based
on external things.

00:03:27.810 --> 00:03:30.780
Very often, we think
happiness will come from,

00:03:30.780 --> 00:03:33.880
and then there's a whole list--

00:03:33.880 --> 00:03:37.030
people, places, situations.

00:03:37.030 --> 00:03:40.410
Happiness comes
from those things.

00:03:40.410 --> 00:03:44.030
And so then we are
left hoping that we

00:03:44.030 --> 00:03:47.260
can manipulate our life
to a certain degrees

00:03:47.260 --> 00:03:49.490
so that happiness will arise.

00:03:49.490 --> 00:03:53.150
But of course, it's
beyond our control.

00:03:53.150 --> 00:03:55.370
And also, I think,
for many people,

00:03:55.370 --> 00:03:58.850
the definition of
happiness is very much

00:03:58.850 --> 00:04:03.270
based on a sensation, a
kind of quick sensation,

00:04:03.270 --> 00:04:05.529
almost like a buzz.

00:04:05.529 --> 00:04:07.320
We have this kind of--
we want to get high.

00:04:07.320 --> 00:04:09.250
We want to feel something.

00:04:09.250 --> 00:04:13.530
Our idea of happiness
is a sensation

00:04:13.530 --> 00:04:17.910
that is triggered by something,
and then we feel good.

00:04:17.910 --> 00:04:21.510
And of course, the problem
with that is it doesn't last.

00:04:21.510 --> 00:04:23.160
So we feel good,
then we feel bad.

00:04:23.160 --> 00:04:25.510
It's very unstable.

00:04:25.510 --> 00:04:29.940
So when our happiness depends
on an external trigger,

00:04:29.940 --> 00:04:32.010
then the problem is when
the trigger is absent,

00:04:32.010 --> 00:04:34.770
the happiness is absent.

00:04:34.770 --> 00:04:37.470
And we're just, in a
way, lurching from one

00:04:37.470 --> 00:04:43.010
high to the next, looking for a
buzz, looking for a sensation.

00:04:43.010 --> 00:04:45.150
And so much of the way we
construct our lives now

00:04:45.150 --> 00:04:49.450
is based on that with our
use of the internet, even

00:04:49.450 --> 00:04:52.660
food, caffeine,
different experiences.

00:04:52.660 --> 00:04:56.230
We construct our life to
give us these sensations that

00:04:56.230 --> 00:04:58.890
make us feel good.

00:04:58.890 --> 00:05:02.690
But the problem is the more
we are hoping that happiness

00:05:02.690 --> 00:05:05.120
will come to us
from the outside,

00:05:05.120 --> 00:05:09.460
the more we feel lacking inside.

00:05:09.460 --> 00:05:11.000
In a way, we're
telling ourselves

00:05:11.000 --> 00:05:13.050
that we are deficient.

00:05:13.050 --> 00:05:13.900
I need this.

00:05:13.900 --> 00:05:14.520
I need that.

00:05:14.520 --> 00:05:15.030
I need that.

00:05:15.030 --> 00:05:16.080
Then I'll be happy.

00:05:16.080 --> 00:05:19.440
So we're creating
a feeling of lack,

00:05:19.440 --> 00:05:21.900
that we lack that happiness.

00:05:21.900 --> 00:05:26.740
We're creating a deficiency
or sense of almost despair,

00:05:26.740 --> 00:05:29.090
and this becomes very painful.

00:05:29.090 --> 00:05:34.030
And then also, the wanting
and the grasping and craving

00:05:34.030 --> 00:05:39.100
that we experience becomes
a habit that creates more

00:05:39.100 --> 00:05:41.590
wanting, grasping, and craving.

00:05:41.590 --> 00:05:44.970
So the wanting leads
to more wanting,

00:05:44.970 --> 00:05:47.370
and then we feel
never satisfied,

00:05:47.370 --> 00:05:51.360
because whatever we
get isn't enough,

00:05:51.360 --> 00:05:55.520
because we're perpetuating
the habit of wanting.

00:05:55.520 --> 00:05:58.190
So then we're jumping
over the experience,

00:05:58.190 --> 00:06:00.270
looking for the next thing.

00:06:00.270 --> 00:06:06.030
So we feel this unsettled
quality in our lives,

00:06:06.030 --> 00:06:10.290
almost like a fear or a
feeling of uncertainty.

00:06:10.290 --> 00:06:12.990
And this feeds us to want more.

00:06:12.990 --> 00:06:15.810
So it's a very vicious cycle.

00:06:15.810 --> 00:06:18.240
And then all the things
that we depend upon

00:06:18.240 --> 00:06:22.680
for our happiness are,
of course, impermanent.

00:06:22.680 --> 00:06:24.940
They're subject to change.

00:06:24.940 --> 00:06:27.000
So there's a feeling
of uncertainty

00:06:27.000 --> 00:06:31.630
because we're depending
on the unreliable.

00:06:31.630 --> 00:06:33.340
And we kind of know that.

00:06:33.340 --> 00:06:35.350
We kind of know that
everything we depend upon

00:06:35.350 --> 00:06:37.720
for our happiness is
unreliable because

00:06:37.720 --> 00:06:39.782
of its changeable nature.

00:06:39.782 --> 00:06:40.990
So we have two problems here.

00:06:40.990 --> 00:06:43.760
We have the problem
of endless wanting

00:06:43.760 --> 00:06:47.980
and the problem of
depending on the unreliable.

00:06:47.980 --> 00:06:52.450
So this kind of happiness
hasn't worked for us.

00:06:52.450 --> 00:06:55.450
It hasn't given us peace.

00:06:55.450 --> 00:07:00.800
It's just made us more
exhausted, more frustrated.

00:07:00.800 --> 00:07:03.620
And I think, through
meditation training,

00:07:03.620 --> 00:07:06.640
we can find a very
different approach.

00:07:06.640 --> 00:07:11.770
Basically, we're looking
for something different--

00:07:11.770 --> 00:07:14.330
happiness from the inside.

00:07:14.330 --> 00:07:16.580
We're recognizing that
happiness and suffering

00:07:16.580 --> 00:07:19.050
are states of mind.

00:07:19.050 --> 00:07:21.740
So of course, they are triggered
by all kinds of situations.

00:07:21.740 --> 00:07:24.530
But ultimately, they
are mind states.

00:07:24.530 --> 00:07:27.790
So if we're looking
at our states of mind,

00:07:27.790 --> 00:07:29.380
and then looking
at the possibility

00:07:29.380 --> 00:07:33.060
to transform those
states of mind,

00:07:33.060 --> 00:07:36.620
then that becomes very fruitful.

00:07:36.620 --> 00:07:39.800
And then, of course, the
problem starts up again,

00:07:39.800 --> 00:07:43.100
because we start meditating
looking for happiness.

00:07:43.100 --> 00:07:46.010
So we're busy meditating,
and then, again,

00:07:46.010 --> 00:07:48.754
trying to get something,
trying to feel something.

00:07:48.754 --> 00:07:50.420
And this is the
struggle for many people

00:07:50.420 --> 00:07:51.920
in meditation, is
they say, it's not

00:07:51.920 --> 00:07:56.040
working because I
don't feel anything.

00:07:56.040 --> 00:07:58.320
I've been at this for this long.

00:07:58.320 --> 00:08:00.270
When am I going to get high?

00:08:00.270 --> 00:08:01.050
Where's the buzz?

00:08:03.810 --> 00:08:06.360
So we want the feeling
because we're very conditions

00:08:06.360 --> 00:08:07.980
to feel something.

00:08:07.980 --> 00:08:10.130
We're in this culture
of looking for a high.

00:08:10.130 --> 00:08:12.510
And then we meditate and
look for the same thing.

00:08:12.510 --> 00:08:16.920
The cycle starts again
of wanting, not getting,

00:08:16.920 --> 00:08:18.540
feeling it's not enough.

00:08:18.540 --> 00:08:20.970
So I think maybe
we could redefine

00:08:20.970 --> 00:08:24.020
our notion of happiness here.

00:08:24.020 --> 00:08:27.300
And instead of looking for some
kind of feeling or sensation--

00:08:27.300 --> 00:08:29.480
which is very temporary,
it comes and it goes--

00:08:29.480 --> 00:08:35.520
instead of that, maybe we
could discover a kind of peace

00:08:35.520 --> 00:08:39.230
within ourselves where
everything is OK.

00:08:39.230 --> 00:08:41.570
Whether things are going
well or not going well,

00:08:41.570 --> 00:08:44.200
everything can be OK.

00:08:44.200 --> 00:08:48.920
Because true happiness
is a state of freedom

00:08:48.920 --> 00:08:52.814
where our mind can
feel calm and positive.

00:08:52.814 --> 00:08:54.980
And when I say calm, I'm
not talking about some kind

00:08:54.980 --> 00:08:57.170
of tranquilized state.

00:08:57.170 --> 00:09:00.930
Often when people hear about
meditation and mindfulness,

00:09:00.930 --> 00:09:03.140
they think, OK, this is
about calming the mind.

00:09:03.140 --> 00:09:06.650
So I'm going to really
bring my stress down.

00:09:06.650 --> 00:09:08.990
I'm really going to calm down.

00:09:08.990 --> 00:09:11.000
And then what
happens to people is

00:09:11.000 --> 00:09:13.370
they think meditation means
you're supposed to get rid

00:09:13.370 --> 00:09:15.230
of all of your thoughts.

00:09:15.230 --> 00:09:18.220
So they have this idea
that the calm state is

00:09:18.220 --> 00:09:21.010
an empty state, a blank state.

00:09:21.010 --> 00:09:26.780
Calming the mind means stilling
everything, stilling the mind.

00:09:26.780 --> 00:09:28.850
And that again becomes
a problem because we're

00:09:28.850 --> 00:09:33.800
struggling to blank out
our thoughts and emotions.

00:09:33.800 --> 00:09:36.320
And we think of meditation
a bit like going to sleep

00:09:36.320 --> 00:09:39.780
or going into a coma,
just going under.

00:09:39.780 --> 00:09:41.430
It's not about going to sleep.

00:09:41.430 --> 00:09:42.840
It's about waking up.

00:09:42.840 --> 00:09:46.020
It's about being present,
being conscious, being aware.

00:09:46.020 --> 00:09:49.740
So then the thoughts and
feelings and distractions

00:09:49.740 --> 00:09:51.870
are actually part of
the whole journey.

00:09:51.870 --> 00:09:53.940
It's all about how
you deal with those.

00:09:53.940 --> 00:09:57.120
It's not about calming them down
so there's nothing happening.

00:09:57.120 --> 00:10:00.070
It's about being
the observer, taking

00:10:00.070 --> 00:10:04.250
the place of the observer, the
one who is aware of the mind.

00:10:04.250 --> 00:10:07.860
And the observer is happy.

00:10:07.860 --> 00:10:09.710
The observer is free.

00:10:09.710 --> 00:10:11.250
Let's think about it this way.

00:10:11.250 --> 00:10:13.820
When you're experiencing
unhappiness,

00:10:13.820 --> 00:10:18.180
when you're
experiencing sadness,

00:10:18.180 --> 00:10:21.480
there's a part of you
that knows you're unhappy.

00:10:21.480 --> 00:10:24.420
And when you meditate,
you become more identified

00:10:24.420 --> 00:10:28.170
with that part that knows
what the mind is doing.

00:10:28.170 --> 00:10:32.290
And that part is not
in the unhappiness.

00:10:32.290 --> 00:10:34.950
That part is able to see it.

00:10:34.950 --> 00:10:38.140
So that awareness is free.

00:10:38.140 --> 00:10:41.300
And the more we can
build our awareness,

00:10:41.300 --> 00:10:43.530
the more freedom we can develop.

00:10:43.530 --> 00:10:46.850
So I think it's important
to stop seeing meditation

00:10:46.850 --> 00:10:49.330
and mindfulness as a way
of just getting rid of

00:10:49.330 --> 00:10:51.710
or removing everything,
but instead,

00:10:51.710 --> 00:10:55.400
a way of becoming the
observer of the mind.

00:10:55.400 --> 00:10:58.380
And this is how we
choose happiness.

00:10:58.380 --> 00:10:59.880
Because when we can
be the observer,

00:10:59.880 --> 00:11:03.600
we can start to make choices.

00:11:03.600 --> 00:11:06.020
Let's look at what happens
to somebody in a meditation

00:11:06.020 --> 00:11:07.970
session.

00:11:07.970 --> 00:11:10.010
They are observing
their breathing.

00:11:10.010 --> 00:11:14.110
That's a very common technique--
focusing on your breathing.

00:11:14.110 --> 00:11:15.860
And then, of course,
within a few seconds,

00:11:15.860 --> 00:11:18.650
the mind starts wandering.

00:11:18.650 --> 00:11:20.660
And then the person starts
punishing themselves

00:11:20.660 --> 00:11:22.890
and saying, I'm a
failure, I can't do this.

00:11:22.890 --> 00:11:24.950
That's not right.

00:11:24.950 --> 00:11:27.230
So instead of feeling
like a failure

00:11:27.230 --> 00:11:30.830
because our mind
wandered, the other option

00:11:30.830 --> 00:11:34.220
would be to simply notice
that the mind wandered

00:11:34.220 --> 00:11:37.870
and then return to
the breath, gently

00:11:37.870 --> 00:11:41.470
and compassionately
returning to the breath.

00:11:41.470 --> 00:11:44.920
This is actually the
meaning of compassion,

00:11:44.920 --> 00:11:46.750
is that you're not
beating yourself up

00:11:46.750 --> 00:11:48.730
for what your mind is doing.

00:11:48.730 --> 00:11:51.150
And also, you're not trying
to chase those thoughts

00:11:51.150 --> 00:11:52.150
and make them different.

00:11:52.150 --> 00:11:54.650
You're just letting
them be how they are.

00:11:54.650 --> 00:11:56.870
That's unconditional love.

00:11:56.870 --> 00:11:58.520
You have a thought or a feeling.

00:11:58.520 --> 00:11:59.987
It's OK the way it is.

00:11:59.987 --> 00:12:01.320
You don't need to get rid of it.

00:12:01.320 --> 00:12:03.590
You don't need more of it.

00:12:03.590 --> 00:12:05.120
It's just fine.

00:12:05.120 --> 00:12:07.560
That's compassion.

00:12:07.560 --> 00:12:09.960
It's fine the way it is.

00:12:09.960 --> 00:12:13.440
And then you return to the
breath, and you carry on,

00:12:13.440 --> 00:12:15.540
and then the mind goes again.

00:12:15.540 --> 00:12:17.030
The mind escapes again.

00:12:17.030 --> 00:12:19.200
The mind floats
off into thoughts,

00:12:19.200 --> 00:12:20.850
and you bring it back.

00:12:20.850 --> 00:12:23.970
And this bringing it
back again and again--

00:12:23.970 --> 00:12:27.790
that's how we're
exercising choice.

00:12:27.790 --> 00:12:32.920
Because it was choiceless
that our mind got distracted.

00:12:32.920 --> 00:12:38.030
And now we're turning around and
bringing it back to the breath.

00:12:38.030 --> 00:12:39.700
We're making that choice.

00:12:39.700 --> 00:12:41.820
I'm coming back here.

00:12:41.820 --> 00:12:44.100
So through meditation
training, we're

00:12:44.100 --> 00:12:47.380
strengthening that
power of choice.

00:12:47.380 --> 00:12:49.050
And then as we
meditate every day,

00:12:49.050 --> 00:12:51.090
regularly, just like
going to the gym,

00:12:51.090 --> 00:12:55.080
lifting weights, exercise,
we're exercising our mind.

00:12:55.080 --> 00:12:57.990
And this is making us stronger.

00:12:57.990 --> 00:13:01.760
So then we can find
that in our life,

00:13:01.760 --> 00:13:08.000
we can become more able to
choose to stay positive.

00:13:08.000 --> 00:13:11.060
Instead of being
automatically dragged

00:13:11.060 --> 00:13:15.470
into negative reactivity,
which is our normal habit,

00:13:15.470 --> 00:13:20.790
we can choose to stay calm and
stay present, stay focused,

00:13:20.790 --> 00:13:22.957
stay positive.

00:13:22.957 --> 00:13:24.540
And what we're doing
is we're choosing

00:13:24.540 --> 00:13:32.150
a happiness that is beyond
triggers and supports and need.

00:13:32.150 --> 00:13:33.815
It's simply an internal
state of being.

00:13:36.990 --> 00:13:40.831
So when we hear this term inner
peace, it sounds very weak,

00:13:40.831 --> 00:13:41.330
doesn't it?

00:13:41.330 --> 00:13:43.760
Inner peace, like
nothing is happening.

00:13:43.760 --> 00:13:46.620
But I think it
means to be at peace

00:13:46.620 --> 00:13:53.300
with your experiences, negative
ones as well as positive ones.

00:13:53.300 --> 00:13:55.702
So say you're
sitting in the car.

00:13:55.702 --> 00:14:00.340
A favorite practice of mine is
to practice mindfulness moments

00:14:00.340 --> 00:14:03.280
when I'm stuck in traffic
or when I'm standing

00:14:03.280 --> 00:14:05.270
in a queue at an airport.

00:14:05.270 --> 00:14:10.120
So these are situations that
normally make us feel wound up,

00:14:10.120 --> 00:14:12.340
irritated, impatient, et cetera.

00:14:12.340 --> 00:14:15.070
So you're choosing
instead to just

00:14:15.070 --> 00:14:17.336
be aware of your body
and your breathing.

00:14:17.336 --> 00:14:18.460
You're sitting in that car.

00:14:18.460 --> 00:14:20.230
You're stuck in traffic.

00:14:20.230 --> 00:14:24.610
Your mind is running into
the impatience or anger,

00:14:24.610 --> 00:14:28.750
and you just pull it back and
go into a sense of presence--

00:14:28.750 --> 00:14:30.910
feeling the ground
under your feet,

00:14:30.910 --> 00:14:32.590
feeling the chair
under your body,

00:14:32.590 --> 00:14:36.150
being aware of your
shoulders, your breathing.

00:14:36.150 --> 00:14:39.750
You're in that mindful state.

00:14:39.750 --> 00:14:42.100
What you've done
in that moment is

00:14:42.100 --> 00:14:46.290
you've reprogrammed yourself.

00:14:46.290 --> 00:14:49.410
Because we normally have
this automatic programming

00:14:49.410 --> 00:14:53.130
of when I'm in a stressful
situation, such as waiting

00:14:53.130 --> 00:14:56.020
for something, I must
react negatively.

00:14:56.020 --> 00:14:57.600
It's not even intellectualized.

00:14:57.600 --> 00:15:01.260
It's very much
part of our habit,

00:15:01.260 --> 00:15:02.970
our habitual way of reacting.

00:15:02.970 --> 00:15:05.550
So instead, we're
changing that and learning

00:15:05.550 --> 00:15:09.000
to just be still and be
calm and be in this moment

00:15:09.000 --> 00:15:12.730
without judging this moment.

00:15:12.730 --> 00:15:14.800
So we're reprogramming
ourselves.

00:15:14.800 --> 00:15:18.070
We're, in a way,
rewiring ourself.

00:15:18.070 --> 00:15:24.330
Instead of having this stressful
situation and negative reaction

00:15:24.330 --> 00:15:28.700
fused together, we have
a stressful situation

00:15:28.700 --> 00:15:34.560
and a relaxed response,
creating a new connection.

00:15:34.560 --> 00:15:38.160
In terms of our brain, we're
building new neural pathways.

00:15:38.160 --> 00:15:41.620
And these become stronger
and stronger and stronger.

00:15:41.620 --> 00:15:44.860
And also, we're
learning happiness.

00:15:44.860 --> 00:15:48.109
Because next time
you're stuck in traffic,

00:15:48.109 --> 00:15:49.150
you can think, oh, great.

00:15:49.150 --> 00:15:53.650
Now I can do that thing that
I learned from that monk.

00:15:53.650 --> 00:15:54.592
So you feel joy.

00:15:54.592 --> 00:15:55.300
You think, great.

00:15:55.300 --> 00:15:55.821
Bring it on.

00:15:55.821 --> 00:15:56.320
Traffic.

00:15:56.320 --> 00:15:56.819
Come on.

00:15:56.819 --> 00:15:58.185
Let's do more.

00:15:58.185 --> 00:16:00.310
It's like going to the gym
and loading more weights

00:16:00.310 --> 00:16:01.560
on the weight-lifting machine.

00:16:01.560 --> 00:16:03.100
You get bigger muscles.

00:16:03.100 --> 00:16:06.640
So life's struggles
and difficulties

00:16:06.640 --> 00:16:12.540
become chances or
opportunities for awakening.

00:16:12.540 --> 00:16:14.850
So then you're almost
looking forward to that.

00:16:14.850 --> 00:16:17.850
I don't mean you're becoming
some kind of masochist who just

00:16:17.850 --> 00:16:19.110
wants everything to go wrong.

00:16:19.110 --> 00:16:23.074
I just mean that you're taking
experiences as they come.

00:16:23.074 --> 00:16:24.990
And when you're stuck
in traffic, you feel OK.

00:16:24.990 --> 00:16:26.220
You feel, in a way, good.

00:16:26.220 --> 00:16:28.800
You want this to happen
because it gives you

00:16:28.800 --> 00:16:31.420
a chance for training.

00:16:31.420 --> 00:16:34.120
And then that shifts
into your relationships.

00:16:34.120 --> 00:16:37.280
Because let's face it--
relationships are the main

00:16:37.280 --> 00:16:39.460
provokers of stress
in our life--

00:16:39.460 --> 00:16:43.220
how people behave, how we
behave, all of that stuff.

00:16:43.220 --> 00:16:47.160
So that becomes your
traffic experience.

00:16:47.160 --> 00:16:50.920
You're with somebody who
you feel uncomfortable,

00:16:50.920 --> 00:16:54.550
and that's your traffic
training, because you're

00:16:54.550 --> 00:16:58.600
learning to meet the obstacle
with a relaxed mind, which

00:16:58.600 --> 00:17:02.310
doesn't mean you've become
passive or like a doormat,

00:17:02.310 --> 00:17:03.570
letting people abuse you.

00:17:03.570 --> 00:17:05.253
It doesn't mean that.

00:17:05.253 --> 00:17:08.430
It simply means you
don't get wound up.

00:17:08.430 --> 00:17:10.869
And it means you can
actually, in a way,

00:17:10.869 --> 00:17:14.160
experience compassion
towards that person.

00:17:14.160 --> 00:17:17.280
Because in the same way as
when you're stuck in traffic

00:17:17.280 --> 00:17:20.640
and you felt somehow
good about the traffic,

00:17:20.640 --> 00:17:23.160
because this is your
chance for training,

00:17:23.160 --> 00:17:26.230
you now feel that this
person is your friend.

00:17:26.230 --> 00:17:29.940
They're presenting you with
an opportunity for training.

00:17:29.940 --> 00:17:33.140
So your heart opens to them.

00:17:33.140 --> 00:17:35.830
And that's compassion.

00:17:35.830 --> 00:17:38.110
You see, for many people,
compassion is very partial.

00:17:38.110 --> 00:17:40.330
It's just an
emotional experience

00:17:40.330 --> 00:17:43.780
that is triggered when you
see small, fluffy animals

00:17:43.780 --> 00:17:46.300
and children, or the vulnerable.

00:17:46.300 --> 00:17:49.210
And of course, that's a
very, very crucial area

00:17:49.210 --> 00:17:49.910
of compassion.

00:17:49.910 --> 00:17:51.285
We see people who
are vulnerable.

00:17:51.285 --> 00:17:52.750
We feel compassion.

00:17:52.750 --> 00:17:55.780
But that's very partial just
in that moment, at that time,

00:17:55.780 --> 00:17:58.900
and it's just an experience
of an emotional reaction that

00:17:58.900 --> 00:18:01.140
comes and goes.

00:18:01.140 --> 00:18:02.640
Whereas what I'm
talking about here,

00:18:02.640 --> 00:18:05.370
through meditation
training, is where

00:18:05.370 --> 00:18:09.180
you're building the networks
of compassion in your behavior.

00:18:09.180 --> 00:18:13.160
In your brain, in your behavior,
you're building those networks.

00:18:13.160 --> 00:18:16.750
Because every time
somebody does something

00:18:16.750 --> 00:18:20.090
or says something that
makes you uncomfortable,

00:18:20.090 --> 00:18:21.210
you don't have to take it.

00:18:21.210 --> 00:18:22.690
You don't have to be a victim.

00:18:22.690 --> 00:18:27.690
But how you feel internally is
the crucial thing, isn't it?

00:18:27.690 --> 00:18:33.770
And if you can see this person
as your compassion tester,

00:18:33.770 --> 00:18:37.280
your opportunity, then
your energy changes,

00:18:37.280 --> 00:18:40.170
and the relationship changes.

00:18:40.170 --> 00:18:44.340
So you're choosing happiness
even in difficult situations.

00:18:44.340 --> 00:18:49.320
Because I think if happiness
is only in certain situations

00:18:49.320 --> 00:18:53.740
when things are going well,
then it's very partial.

00:18:53.740 --> 00:18:57.630
But if you're choosing to be
happy, even against the odds,

00:18:57.630 --> 00:19:00.315
then you're really in
charge of your life.

00:19:03.040 --> 00:19:05.250
But of course, we
have to train in this.

00:19:05.250 --> 00:19:08.670
This is work.

00:19:08.670 --> 00:19:10.020
This is work.

00:19:10.020 --> 00:19:10.830
We need to train.

00:19:10.830 --> 00:19:15.870
We need to put effort
into daily meditation.

00:19:15.870 --> 00:19:18.480
And I think many people find
that difficult because they're

00:19:18.480 --> 00:19:21.660
so busy, and meditation is
the last thing on the list,

00:19:21.660 --> 00:19:24.826
and then we're too tired,
all of those things.

00:19:24.826 --> 00:19:26.700
But I think, actually,
the main reason people

00:19:26.700 --> 00:19:31.620
struggle to meditate every
day is because of grasping.

00:19:31.620 --> 00:19:33.780
It's because of a sense
of hidden grasping,

00:19:33.780 --> 00:19:37.980
a hidden agenda, which is I
want the meditation to make

00:19:37.980 --> 00:19:39.984
me feel good.

00:19:39.984 --> 00:19:42.130
It's a hidden agenda.

00:19:42.130 --> 00:19:43.280
It's got to feel nice.

00:19:43.280 --> 00:19:45.750
And if it doesn't feel
nice, it's not worth doing.

00:19:45.750 --> 00:19:47.680
And then, of course,
that doesn't happen,

00:19:47.680 --> 00:19:49.205
so then we don't
want to meditate.

00:19:49.205 --> 00:19:50.980
We want to do other stuff.

00:19:50.980 --> 00:19:52.930
We don't drink five
coffees in a row

00:19:52.930 --> 00:19:56.090
because that makes us
feel better, or whatever.

00:19:56.090 --> 00:19:56.990
We want things.

00:19:56.990 --> 00:19:57.680
We want people.

00:19:57.680 --> 00:19:58.780
We want situations.

00:19:58.780 --> 00:20:00.380
That's feeding us
very instantly.

00:20:00.380 --> 00:20:03.920
The meditation doesn't
give us an instant hit.

00:20:03.920 --> 00:20:06.650
So it becomes much harder to
stay committed to something

00:20:06.650 --> 00:20:08.862
that's not giving you a hit.

00:20:08.862 --> 00:20:11.570
It's really hard.

00:20:11.570 --> 00:20:15.650
So I think the solution
is to do two things.

00:20:15.650 --> 00:20:19.720
One is to learn how to practice
tiny moments of meditation

00:20:19.720 --> 00:20:21.114
throughout the day.

00:20:21.114 --> 00:20:22.780
I'm not saying that
will give you a hit,

00:20:22.780 --> 00:20:26.710
but I'm just saying it's easy to
just drop into a mindful state

00:20:26.710 --> 00:20:29.170
while you're washing your
hands, or brushing your teeth,

00:20:29.170 --> 00:20:32.650
or stuck in traffic,
because it's just a moment.

00:20:32.650 --> 00:20:34.060
You're not requiring time.

00:20:34.060 --> 00:20:36.280
You're just momentarily
going into that state

00:20:36.280 --> 00:20:37.380
throughout the day.

00:20:37.380 --> 00:20:41.330
And what happens to you
is you start to notice

00:20:41.330 --> 00:20:43.207
that this is quite pleasurable.

00:20:43.207 --> 00:20:44.540
You're not looking for pleasure.

00:20:44.540 --> 00:20:46.970
You're not looking
for a feeling.

00:20:46.970 --> 00:20:49.220
But as the mindfulness builds
up throughout your day,

00:20:49.220 --> 00:20:53.960
you start to feel good, because
you start to feel at peace,

00:20:53.960 --> 00:20:56.520
and you start to feel nourished.

00:20:56.520 --> 00:21:01.750
It brings an enormous amount
of nourishment into your being

00:21:01.750 --> 00:21:03.750
because you're being
present, you're being calm,

00:21:03.750 --> 00:21:06.540
you're not going with
negative reactivity.

00:21:06.540 --> 00:21:09.550
This is really enriching.

00:21:09.550 --> 00:21:13.810
And this gets you
wanting to meditate more.

00:21:13.810 --> 00:21:15.220
So that's one thing.

00:21:15.220 --> 00:21:17.670
Another thing which
really helps if you

00:21:17.670 --> 00:21:20.130
find it hard to
meditate regularly

00:21:20.130 --> 00:21:23.880
is to occasionally develop
some kind of wisdom

00:21:23.880 --> 00:21:26.550
about the process
of meditation, which

00:21:26.550 --> 00:21:29.880
means to spend time thinking
about why meditation

00:21:29.880 --> 00:21:31.859
is important.

00:21:31.859 --> 00:21:34.150
And the best way to do this
is to actually ask yourself

00:21:34.150 --> 00:21:38.790
simple questions, such as where
does happiness really come

00:21:38.790 --> 00:21:41.150
from.

00:21:41.150 --> 00:21:44.720
Where does happiness
really come from?

00:21:44.720 --> 00:21:48.560
And where does suffering
really come from?

00:21:48.560 --> 00:21:50.610
They come from the mind.

00:21:50.610 --> 00:21:53.700
They are mind states.

00:21:53.700 --> 00:21:57.300
And what happens if I
change my mind state?

00:21:57.300 --> 00:22:00.020
What happens if I train my mind?

00:22:00.020 --> 00:22:02.870
How does this address
the deep question

00:22:02.870 --> 00:22:05.310
of happiness and suffering?

00:22:05.310 --> 00:22:09.140
So if you ask yourself that,
it helps you to remember that

00:22:09.140 --> 00:22:13.850
actually, in life, all we
want is happiness and freedom

00:22:13.850 --> 00:22:17.930
from pain, and all the things
we're doing to get that

00:22:17.930 --> 00:22:21.140
are only working to
a certain degree.

00:22:21.140 --> 00:22:25.160
But if happiness and freedom
from pain are mind states,

00:22:25.160 --> 00:22:30.630
then surely, training our mind
is the way to get what we want.

00:22:30.630 --> 00:22:34.130
So when you realize that
meditation will actually

00:22:34.130 --> 00:22:36.930
give you what you wanted
from all those other things

00:22:36.930 --> 00:22:39.839
but weren't getting
in the long run,

00:22:39.839 --> 00:22:41.380
when you realize
it's a long journey,

00:22:41.380 --> 00:22:43.170
but it will give
you what you wanted,

00:22:43.170 --> 00:22:44.507
then you want to meditate.

00:22:44.507 --> 00:22:45.965
This gives you
energy for practice.

00:22:48.470 --> 00:22:51.580
So I think I've covered
a few points here.

00:22:51.580 --> 00:22:53.860
I've been talking
about happiness

00:22:53.860 --> 00:22:57.550
and the choice of choosing
happiness, learning

00:22:57.550 --> 00:23:00.310
where happiness comes from,
and the link with meditation

00:23:00.310 --> 00:23:01.504
practice.

00:23:01.504 --> 00:23:02.920
And I think a
really crucial thing

00:23:02.920 --> 00:23:08.590
to take away from this is that
meditation requires letting go

00:23:08.590 --> 00:23:11.210
rather than grasping.

00:23:11.210 --> 00:23:14.045
We tend to live in such
a grasping culture.

00:23:14.045 --> 00:23:16.780
We're always wanting something.

00:23:16.780 --> 00:23:19.060
And then when we
meditate, it's really hard

00:23:19.060 --> 00:23:21.260
not to grasp after results.

00:23:21.260 --> 00:23:24.340
But I it's really important
just to have some time when

00:23:24.340 --> 00:23:27.220
we totally let go and
just experience our mind,

00:23:27.220 --> 00:23:29.180
whether it's busy or not busy.

00:23:29.180 --> 00:23:32.569
There's no such thing as good
meditation or bad meditation.

00:23:32.569 --> 00:23:34.360
Some people have a
session where their mind

00:23:34.360 --> 00:23:37.785
is just crazy, crazy, just
rolling around like a--

00:23:37.785 --> 00:23:40.030
I don't know-- like
a spinning top,

00:23:40.030 --> 00:23:41.770
and they feel it
was a bad session.

00:23:41.770 --> 00:23:44.830
To me, that's a good
session, because you

00:23:44.830 --> 00:23:48.760
saw your mind in all its glory.

00:23:48.760 --> 00:23:52.290
You're experiencing
the busy mind.

00:23:52.290 --> 00:23:53.265
That's a good session.

00:23:53.265 --> 00:23:53.765
That's work.

00:23:56.540 --> 00:23:59.110
That's a good workout.

00:23:59.110 --> 00:24:02.200
So maybe we need to move
away from this judgment

00:24:02.200 --> 00:24:06.220
around what a good session
and a bad session is.

00:24:06.220 --> 00:24:09.350
And I think then we can
experience more freedom

00:24:09.350 --> 00:24:12.830
and greater compassion.

00:24:12.830 --> 00:24:15.770
So I want to stop there
and now open this up

00:24:15.770 --> 00:24:17.570
