And I just remember sitting
there with my legs on fire.

00:27:27.926 --> 00:27:29.550
I had to sit cross-legged
on the floor.

00:27:29.550 --> 00:27:31.614
My legs and my back on fire.

00:27:31.614 --> 00:27:33.780
And there was a carpet in
front of me with patterns,

00:27:33.780 --> 00:27:35.238
and I was looking
at these patterns

00:27:35.238 --> 00:27:38.940
to just try and stay alive.

00:27:38.940 --> 00:27:42.010
Just focus on that pattern,
and you won't go crazy.

00:27:42.010 --> 00:27:43.710
So that was extreme.

00:27:43.710 --> 00:27:48.360
And then, of course, I learned
how to build it up slowly

00:27:48.360 --> 00:27:51.390
and do smaller sessions.

00:27:51.390 --> 00:27:54.000
But one of the challenges
I found earlier on,

00:27:54.000 --> 00:27:56.100
which I addressed
in this talk, is

00:27:56.100 --> 00:28:02.000
that I really was searching
for a feeling all the time.

00:28:02.000 --> 00:28:06.220
And there was a period where I
was doing a lot of meditation

00:28:06.220 --> 00:28:10.940
and getting very depressed
and feeling very--

00:28:10.940 --> 00:28:11.930
almost like let down.

00:28:11.930 --> 00:28:14.330
It was a heavy feeling.

00:28:14.330 --> 00:28:18.120
And I spoke to my teacher,
[INAUDIBLE] Rinpoche, and he--

00:28:18.120 --> 00:28:22.460
I told him about this,
and he said, actually,

00:28:22.460 --> 00:28:24.130
you're like somebody
who's taking drugs.

00:28:24.130 --> 00:28:25.847
You're using the
meditation like a drug.

00:28:25.847 --> 00:28:26.930
You're trying to get high.

00:28:26.930 --> 00:28:28.554
And I realized that's
what I was doing.

00:28:28.554 --> 00:28:31.160
I was sitting down
to try and ramp up

00:28:31.160 --> 00:28:33.914
some sensation in
my mind or my body.

00:28:33.914 --> 00:28:36.080
And of course, because
you're looking for something,

00:28:36.080 --> 00:28:38.540
you're feeling the lack of that.

00:28:38.540 --> 00:28:43.100
And so he showed me how to work
through that, and instead--

00:28:43.100 --> 00:28:46.190
there really has to be a
motivation of compassion.

00:28:46.190 --> 00:28:48.770
Even if you're just meditating
for stress reduction,

00:28:48.770 --> 00:28:49.800
that's not enough.

00:28:49.800 --> 00:28:52.640
There's got to be a feeling
that this is not just

00:28:52.640 --> 00:28:54.290
about me, but about others.

00:28:54.290 --> 00:28:56.000
And you're dedicating
your practice

00:28:56.000 --> 00:28:59.880
to the happiness of all,
the happiness of others.

00:28:59.880 --> 00:29:03.810
And then this removes
the grasping--

00:29:03.810 --> 00:29:05.510
not all of it, but some of it--

00:29:05.510 --> 00:29:08.640
and also gives a
sense of a journey.

00:29:08.640 --> 00:29:10.730
SPEAKER: And at this stage
for you, do you still

00:29:10.730 --> 00:29:14.010
find it hard to let
go of the grasping

00:29:14.010 --> 00:29:15.840
and always have the
right intention?

00:29:15.840 --> 00:29:17.340
Do you still struggle?

00:29:17.340 --> 00:29:19.131
GELONG THUBTEN: Of
course I still struggle.

00:29:21.120 --> 00:29:24.270
This whole idea of having
the right intention that--

00:29:24.270 --> 00:29:27.240
in Buddhism, we talk about
having the motivation to free

00:29:27.240 --> 00:29:29.490
all beings from
suffering, and this

00:29:29.490 --> 00:29:32.490
needs to be your
motivation for practice.

00:29:32.490 --> 00:29:35.310
So I could really give
myself a hard time about that

00:29:35.310 --> 00:29:36.750
and say, well,
that's not genuine.

00:29:36.750 --> 00:29:39.720
I'm not experiencing that
much, and my motivation

00:29:39.720 --> 00:29:40.540
is not good enough.

00:29:40.540 --> 00:29:44.700
But I actually think wanting
to have good motivation

00:29:44.700 --> 00:29:46.105
is good motivation.

00:29:46.105 --> 00:29:48.840
It's almost like wanting to
be more compassionate means

00:29:48.840 --> 00:29:50.640
you already are compassionate.

00:29:50.640 --> 00:29:54.330
And that's the way I relax
myself about this stuff.

00:29:54.330 --> 00:29:55.830
When I'm struggling
with this stuff,

00:29:55.830 --> 00:30:00.110
I say, actually, I'm
doing my best, so it's OK.

00:30:00.110 --> 00:30:03.150
I'm much gentler on
myself than I used to be.

00:30:03.150 --> 00:30:06.325
That's changed a lot
through meditation.

00:30:06.325 --> 00:30:08.700
SPEAKER: I suppose it's a
common challenge for a lot when

00:30:08.700 --> 00:30:11.250
you beat yourself with
a stick when it wasn't

00:30:11.250 --> 00:30:12.567
a good meditation session.

00:30:12.567 --> 00:30:14.150
GELONG THUBTEN: It
wasn't good enough.

00:30:14.150 --> 00:30:15.110
It wasn't authentic.

00:30:15.110 --> 00:30:15.990
It wasn't this.

00:30:15.990 --> 00:30:16.640
It wasn't that.

00:30:16.640 --> 00:30:18.260
That's just another judgment.

00:30:18.260 --> 00:30:21.080
That's another
thing to let go of.

00:30:21.080 --> 00:30:24.470
SPEAKER: And-- along
those lines of what's good

00:30:24.470 --> 00:30:26.960
and what's bad-- so a
lot of people sometimes,

00:30:26.960 --> 00:30:30.110
me included, when you're
feeling good, then OK,

00:30:30.110 --> 00:30:33.689
and whatever is around
you is benefiting you.

00:30:33.689 --> 00:30:35.105
To meditate, you
sit and meditate.

00:30:35.105 --> 00:30:36.770
But when you're sick,
when you're ill,

00:30:36.770 --> 00:30:39.040
when you don't feel
good, you're like, no, I

00:30:39.040 --> 00:30:40.580
don't need meditation now.

00:30:40.580 --> 00:30:43.220
Or vise versa-- sometimes
people really only

00:30:43.220 --> 00:30:44.590
meditate when they're stressed.

00:30:44.590 --> 00:30:46.423
And when they're really
happy, they're like,

00:30:46.423 --> 00:30:49.220
I don't need medication
because I'm already happy.

00:30:49.220 --> 00:30:52.772
GELONG THUBTEN: The first one
is more common, which is--

00:30:52.772 --> 00:30:54.980
both are true, and the first
one is even more common,

00:30:54.980 --> 00:30:58.250
which is where, if you're tired,
you're sick, you're unhappy,

00:30:58.250 --> 00:31:00.110
you think, oh, I'll
meditate later.

00:31:00.110 --> 00:31:03.860
I'm not in the right state
for it to be a good session.

00:31:03.860 --> 00:31:08.480
And this is really a
deceptive motivation.

00:31:08.480 --> 00:31:11.820
Because what happens then
is you're telling yourself,

00:31:11.820 --> 00:31:14.690
I have to feel a certain way
for my meditation to work.

00:31:14.690 --> 00:31:18.300
I can only meditate when I
feel like it, when I feel good.

00:31:18.300 --> 00:31:19.400
And that's not meditation.

00:31:19.400 --> 00:31:21.630
Then it's again back
to that grasping.

00:31:21.630 --> 00:31:25.310
So I think it's really important
to meditate when you're tired,

00:31:25.310 --> 00:31:27.590
when you're sick,
when you're unhappy.

00:31:27.590 --> 00:31:30.230
Because you're just being
with that experience

00:31:30.230 --> 00:31:32.120
in an unconditional way.

00:31:32.120 --> 00:31:34.970
And that is how you make
friends with yourself,

00:31:34.970 --> 00:31:37.312
all aspects of yourself.

00:31:37.312 --> 00:31:39.770
Otherwise, you're just showing
up at the meditation cushion

00:31:39.770 --> 00:31:40.890
when you're in a good mood.

00:31:40.890 --> 00:31:43.014
It's like you're having a
very partial relationship

00:31:43.014 --> 00:31:45.560
with yourself, like a
fair-weather friend.

00:31:45.560 --> 00:31:48.184
When I'm in a good mood,
then I'll sit with my mind.

00:31:48.184 --> 00:31:49.850
But when my mind is
not in a good state,

00:31:49.850 --> 00:31:51.330
I'm going to reject it.

00:31:51.330 --> 00:31:55.120
So instead, if you meditate
when you're unwell,

00:31:55.120 --> 00:31:57.850
you're making friends with your
experience in a very genuine,

00:31:57.850 --> 00:32:00.892
compassionate way.

00:32:00.892 --> 00:32:02.600
SPEAKER: Does anybody
have any questions,

00:32:02.600 --> 00:32:06.050
or should I keep going?

00:32:06.050 --> 00:32:09.590
AUDIENCE: So you were
speaking about the experience

00:32:09.590 --> 00:32:11.690
of being stuck in traffic.

00:32:11.690 --> 00:32:15.100
So I wonder if any
of the techniques

00:32:15.100 --> 00:32:19.130
may be applied to the situation
where you are actually driving.

00:32:19.130 --> 00:32:23.180
So I wonder whether
being mindful

00:32:23.180 --> 00:32:26.540
may get in the way of doing
some important work that

00:32:26.540 --> 00:32:29.260
requires being focused
on something external.

00:32:29.260 --> 00:32:31.820
GELONG THUBTEN: Well,
actually, just to drive a car,

00:32:31.820 --> 00:32:34.230
you are being mindful.

00:32:34.230 --> 00:32:37.310
Everyone has a natural
kind of mindfulness.

00:32:37.310 --> 00:32:39.500
To drive a car, you
have to be mindful.

00:32:39.500 --> 00:32:41.790
Otherwise, your car
is going to crash.

00:32:41.790 --> 00:32:45.710
So there is already a
level of mindfulness there.

00:32:45.710 --> 00:32:49.280
And I think it's important
to see mindfulness

00:32:49.280 --> 00:32:51.890
as you're being really present.

00:32:51.890 --> 00:32:53.120
You're not switched off.

00:32:53.120 --> 00:32:56.150
Some people like to close
their eyes and go within.

00:32:56.150 --> 00:32:57.960
That's not what
I'm talking about.

00:32:57.960 --> 00:33:00.355
I'm talking about being
totally in this moment.

00:33:00.355 --> 00:33:01.730
So when you're
driving a car, you

00:33:01.730 --> 00:33:03.797
have to be totally
in this moment.

00:33:03.797 --> 00:33:05.630
But what many people
do is they drive a car,

00:33:05.630 --> 00:33:08.219
and they are partially
mindful of what's going on.

00:33:08.219 --> 00:33:10.760
And then they're listening to
music and chatting to a friend,

00:33:10.760 --> 00:33:13.440
and there's very
split attention.

00:33:13.440 --> 00:33:15.860
But you could drive
completely mindfully,

00:33:15.860 --> 00:33:17.547
and that could be meditation.

00:33:20.687 --> 00:33:21.770
AUDIENCE: So I basically--

00:33:21.770 --> 00:33:24.990
I have two comments, and I was
hoping you can reflect on it.

00:33:24.990 --> 00:33:28.380
So the first
comment is why isn't

00:33:28.380 --> 00:33:31.260
being more aware and a state
of freedom the default.

00:33:31.260 --> 00:33:33.420
Why is it such a
challenge for us?

00:33:33.420 --> 00:33:39.600
And secondly, I was wondering,
are we not actually choosing--

00:33:39.600 --> 00:33:41.220
not per se happiness,
but to be more

00:33:41.220 --> 00:33:45.490
in control of the
different states of being?

00:33:45.490 --> 00:33:47.760
So it's more like a
control issue, almost.

00:33:47.760 --> 00:33:50.010
If you have more awareness
of all the states of being,

00:33:50.010 --> 00:33:51.570
then you feel in control.

00:33:51.570 --> 00:33:55.890
You're not as much into either
being happy or suffering.

00:33:55.890 --> 00:34:00.760
So basically, the two comments
are why it's not the default

00:34:00.760 --> 00:34:05.640
and why it's not more
about building awareness

00:34:05.640 --> 00:34:08.159
to feel more in control.

00:34:08.159 --> 00:34:09.659
GELONG THUBTEN:
Well, in a way, when

00:34:09.659 --> 00:34:14.370
you say happiness and
freedom and default,

00:34:14.370 --> 00:34:16.469
in the Buddhist
understanding, we

00:34:16.469 --> 00:34:20.040
believe that our
natural mind is pure.

00:34:20.040 --> 00:34:24.929
Our deeper mind is free.

00:34:24.929 --> 00:34:28.710
We call it Buddha nature, which
is that deep down inside, we

00:34:28.710 --> 00:34:31.139
have the potential
for awakening.

00:34:31.139 --> 00:34:34.260
And in fact, every time you sit
down on a chair or a cushion

00:34:34.260 --> 00:34:37.260
to meditate, you're
acknowledging that potential.

00:34:37.260 --> 00:34:39.150
Because why would
you do something

00:34:39.150 --> 00:34:41.550
unless you felt you
had the potential

00:34:41.550 --> 00:34:43.330
to achieve the results of it?

00:34:43.330 --> 00:34:46.420
So you're meditating because you
know there's something deeper.

00:34:46.420 --> 00:34:51.239
So in a way, our natural state
is happy and pure and free.

00:34:51.239 --> 00:34:53.790
But it's layered with confusion.

00:34:53.790 --> 00:34:55.320
We get caught up in confusion.

00:34:55.320 --> 00:34:56.820
We get addicted to confusion.

00:34:56.820 --> 00:34:59.730
And a lot of that is
to do with survival--

00:34:59.730 --> 00:35:03.470
the survival instinct, the
fight or flight reaction.

00:35:03.470 --> 00:35:07.980
In a way, our brain is wired
to obsess about what's wrong

00:35:07.980 --> 00:35:11.650
and what's dangerous, because
that's how we stay alive.

00:35:11.650 --> 00:35:14.850
But much deeper than that
is pure consciousness

00:35:14.850 --> 00:35:18.360
that we can learn to slowly
access through meditation.

00:35:18.360 --> 00:35:19.950
And then the second
comment around--

00:35:19.950 --> 00:35:21.290
actually, I've forgotten
your second comment.

00:35:21.290 --> 00:35:22.240
It was really intense.

00:35:22.240 --> 00:35:25.020
So can you repeat it?

00:35:25.020 --> 00:35:29.620
AUDIENCE: So are we not
choosing to be more aware?

00:35:29.620 --> 00:35:30.870
GELONG THUBTEN: In meditation?

00:35:30.870 --> 00:35:32.340
AUDIENCE: Yeah, in meditation.

00:35:32.340 --> 00:35:34.500
Instead of-- OK, we're
not choosing happiness,

00:35:34.500 --> 00:35:36.360
but it's more like
we're choosing

00:35:36.360 --> 00:35:39.960
to be more aware of our
different states of beings.

00:35:39.960 --> 00:35:42.300
Thereby, we build
up more control of--

00:35:42.300 --> 00:35:45.540
either we are in this happy
mode or this suffering mode,

00:35:45.540 --> 00:35:47.410
yes or no?

00:35:47.410 --> 00:35:49.790
Basically, our
capability to zoom out

00:35:49.790 --> 00:35:51.870
is built by the meditation.

00:35:51.870 --> 00:35:54.167
GELONG THUBTEN: I don't
know about control.

00:35:54.167 --> 00:35:56.250
I don't know if we're
controlling our mind states.

00:35:56.250 --> 00:36:00.720
I think it's that we're
learning to let go.

00:36:00.720 --> 00:36:02.940
So it's a bit like
traffic on a road.

00:36:02.940 --> 00:36:05.430
You have cars going by.

00:36:05.430 --> 00:36:07.800
Are you getting into the
cars and going for drives,

00:36:07.800 --> 00:36:09.690
or are you just
letting the cars go by?

00:36:09.690 --> 00:36:10.920
And then maybe you
could choose to get

00:36:10.920 --> 00:36:12.390
into the useful
cars, the cars that

00:36:12.390 --> 00:36:14.280
take you somewhere positive.

00:36:14.280 --> 00:36:16.230
So it's about making choice.

00:36:16.230 --> 00:36:19.860
I find the term "control" makes
me think of something very

00:36:19.860 --> 00:36:22.230
tight and rigid and repressive.

00:36:22.230 --> 00:36:24.990
I'm talking about
freedom and choice.

00:36:24.990 --> 00:36:26.440
Does that make sense?

00:36:26.440 --> 00:36:26.940
Cool.

00:36:26.940 --> 00:36:27.700
Thank you.

00:36:32.310 --> 00:36:34.230
AUDIENCE: Do you
think that you're

00:36:34.230 --> 00:36:36.990
more free if you control
your own mind or more free

00:36:36.990 --> 00:36:39.240
if the mind controls you?

00:36:39.240 --> 00:36:42.090
GELONG THUBTEN: Well, let's
dump this word "control."

00:36:42.090 --> 00:36:47.700
I think you can be
more free if you can

00:36:47.700 --> 00:36:51.300
choose what your mind is doing.

00:36:51.300 --> 00:36:53.800
Do you understand
why I'm slightly

00:36:53.800 --> 00:36:55.660
hesitant about the
term "control?"

00:36:55.660 --> 00:37:01.420
Because it sounds like you're
making your mind very tense,

00:37:01.420 --> 00:37:03.640
controlling what it
does, pushing down

00:37:03.640 --> 00:37:05.876
the negative
thoughts and jumping

00:37:05.876 --> 00:37:07.000
into the positive thoughts.

00:37:07.000 --> 00:37:10.310
That, to me, feels
very stressful.

00:37:10.310 --> 00:37:11.140
Yeah?

00:37:11.140 --> 00:37:16.810
So can we rephrase this and
think more in terms of freedom?

00:37:16.810 --> 00:37:18.700
And your question
was are you choosing

00:37:18.700 --> 00:37:19.970
or is the mind choosing you.

00:37:19.970 --> 00:37:22.550
And like I started
my talk today,

00:37:22.550 --> 00:37:25.990
it really feels like
stuff chooses us.

00:37:25.990 --> 00:37:28.870
Suddenly, we're experiencing
sadness, and we're thinking,

00:37:28.870 --> 00:37:29.800
I didn't ask for this.

00:37:29.800 --> 00:37:31.640
Where did this come from?

00:37:31.640 --> 00:37:33.640
And then we think
somebody put it in us.

00:37:33.640 --> 00:37:35.860
We immediately point the finger.

00:37:35.860 --> 00:37:37.825
Oh, it must be you.

00:37:37.825 --> 00:37:38.950
Why am I feeling like this?

00:37:38.950 --> 00:37:41.530
It must be you, or
it must be this.

00:37:41.530 --> 00:37:45.280
And so it feels like these mind
states are invading or choosing

00:37:45.280 --> 00:37:47.800
us, and sticking
to us like glue.

00:37:47.800 --> 00:37:50.710
And I think meditation is about
changing it round so that you

00:37:50.710 --> 00:37:52.960
are the one who is creating.

00:37:52.960 --> 00:37:56.370
You are creating your
thoughts and emotions,

00:37:56.370 --> 00:37:58.810
and you are learning how
to create the right ones

00:37:58.810 --> 00:38:01.870
and just let go of the
ones that harm you.

00:38:01.870 --> 00:38:02.450
Thank you.

00:38:05.500 --> 00:38:07.950
AUDIENCE: So I actually
also have two questions.

00:38:07.950 --> 00:38:10.960
For one, it's mindfulness--

00:38:10.960 --> 00:38:12.610
we want to be present
in this moment.

00:38:12.610 --> 00:38:15.945
But I guess a lot of people here
have days that we plan ahead.

00:38:15.945 --> 00:38:17.590
We plan our next day.

00:38:17.590 --> 00:38:19.820
We plan our next week, our year.

00:38:19.820 --> 00:38:24.100
So how do you
suggest we do this?

00:38:24.100 --> 00:38:27.580
How do we plan, but
we still stay mindful?

00:38:27.580 --> 00:38:30.400
GELONG THUBTEN: So yeah,
we do need to plan.

00:38:30.400 --> 00:38:34.180
And it often sounds like
a contradiction when

00:38:34.180 --> 00:38:37.380
we say mindfulness is about
being in the present moment,

00:38:37.380 --> 00:38:39.575
and then, we've
got to plan stuff.

00:38:39.575 --> 00:38:41.950
Are we supposed to just live
in the present all the time?

00:38:41.950 --> 00:38:44.830
If you lived in the present
all the time, you wouldn't eat.

00:38:44.830 --> 00:38:46.870
You wouldn't plan--
you know what I mean?

00:38:46.870 --> 00:38:48.130
You're planning your meal.

00:38:48.130 --> 00:38:50.560
So again, it's to
do with choice.

00:38:50.560 --> 00:38:52.420
I think we plan obsessively.

00:38:52.420 --> 00:38:53.620
We plan impulsively.

00:38:53.620 --> 00:38:59.590
We plan in a way that becomes
so habitual that we never

00:38:59.590 --> 00:39:01.180
actually arrive.

00:39:01.180 --> 00:39:03.280
Because when we get to
the thing we planned,

00:39:03.280 --> 00:39:05.260
we're busy planning
the next thing.

00:39:05.260 --> 00:39:07.660
So how about
planning the choice?

00:39:07.660 --> 00:39:09.700
How about choosing
to plan, as and when

00:39:09.700 --> 00:39:12.430
you need to plan,
and then let go?

00:39:12.430 --> 00:39:15.904
Make plans, do what you need
to do, but let go of outcomes.

00:39:15.904 --> 00:39:17.320
That would be a
much healthier way

00:39:17.320 --> 00:39:19.900
of making our plans
actually succeed.

00:39:19.900 --> 00:39:22.384
What was your second question?

00:39:22.384 --> 00:39:23.800
AUDIENCE: So with
