And so that's what
kept me going.

00:51:05.470 --> 00:51:08.630
And then eventually, through
the help of my teachers

00:51:08.630 --> 00:51:10.640
and then my own
commitment, I was

00:51:10.640 --> 00:51:12.170
able to connect
with the practice,

00:51:12.170 --> 00:51:13.170
and then things changed.

00:51:16.590 --> 00:51:19.140
AUDIENCE: So overall, Googlers
tend to be quite data-driven.

00:51:19.140 --> 00:51:20.640
And I'm wondering
about your opinion

00:51:20.640 --> 00:51:22.707
about actually
measuring happiness.

00:51:22.707 --> 00:51:24.540
So most of the time,
it's a scale out of 10,

00:51:24.540 --> 00:51:27.589
so putting absolute numbers
to such a subjective thing.

00:51:27.589 --> 00:51:29.880
GELONG THUBTEN: I don't know
about measuring happiness,

00:51:29.880 --> 00:51:32.820
because then you start
to grasp after results.

00:51:35.610 --> 00:51:37.000
Yeah, we're all data-driven.

00:51:37.000 --> 00:51:40.110
We're all in measures
and evaluations.

00:51:40.110 --> 00:51:46.230
And can we maybe take
meditation and happiness away

00:51:46.230 --> 00:51:47.880
from that world
and have some time

00:51:47.880 --> 00:51:52.540
when we're just not driven,
and we can just let go and be?

00:51:52.540 --> 00:51:55.825
I think that's crucial in
a data-driven environment.

00:51:55.825 --> 00:51:57.700
And that's what I've
been talking about a lot

00:51:57.700 --> 00:52:00.490
here when I'm doing these
regular classes at Google,

00:52:00.490 --> 00:52:03.250
is can we have some time when
we just switch off all of that

00:52:03.250 --> 00:52:05.320
and go into a sense of being.

00:52:05.320 --> 00:52:07.010
I think that would be great.

00:52:07.010 --> 00:52:09.670
And then go back to the data,
but bringing the being with you

00:52:09.670 --> 00:52:11.970
into the data.

00:52:11.970 --> 00:52:14.545
Thank you.

00:52:14.545 --> 00:52:18.480
SPEAKER: I'll just
ask one last question

00:52:18.480 --> 00:52:20.810
since you mentioned
data and you mentioned

00:52:20.810 --> 00:52:23.580
working with a
neuroscientist on the book.

00:52:23.580 --> 00:52:25.130
I was just wondering if you--

00:52:25.130 --> 00:52:27.590
from a science perspective,
what is the one thing

00:52:27.590 --> 00:52:31.060
you learned about meditation
from the neuroscientist that

00:52:31.060 --> 00:52:33.997
was interesting from a
scientific perspective?

00:52:33.997 --> 00:52:36.080
GELONG THUBTEN: Yeah, it's
been really interesting

00:52:36.080 --> 00:52:36.920
working with Ash.

00:52:36.920 --> 00:52:37.970
He's a neuroscientist.

00:52:37.970 --> 00:52:42.030
So Ruby Wax, Ash Ranpura, and
myself did this book together,

00:52:42.030 --> 00:52:47.000
and it was an amazing
conversation about the mind

00:52:47.000 --> 00:52:48.800
and the heart and the brain.

00:52:48.800 --> 00:52:52.540
And I learned a lot
from Ash about--

00:52:52.540 --> 00:52:55.500
well, OK, so what meditation
does to your brain--

00:52:55.500 --> 00:52:58.750
there's proof that it works--
but more interestingly,

00:52:58.750 --> 00:53:01.864
this whole notion of creating
habits and changing them.

00:53:01.864 --> 00:53:03.280
He gave a really
beautiful example

00:53:03.280 --> 00:53:06.280
where he said the brain
is a bit like a field,

00:53:06.280 --> 00:53:10.170
a field with lots of grass.

00:53:10.170 --> 00:53:11.790
And there's no path.

00:53:11.790 --> 00:53:15.500
And one person walks
and makes a path.

00:53:15.500 --> 00:53:18.000
A second person walks and
makes a path, a third person.

00:53:18.000 --> 00:53:20.250
Eventually, that path--
the grass is flattened,

00:53:20.250 --> 00:53:22.680
and there's a path, and
you can easily go down it.

00:53:22.680 --> 00:53:24.720
And he said that's
what meditation does.

00:53:24.720 --> 00:53:26.250
You're creating
neural pathways that

00:53:26.250 --> 00:53:28.380
become more and more
natural, and that's

00:53:28.380 --> 00:53:30.030
how you can be happy.

00:53:30.030 --> 00:53:34.200
So I learned a lot from
Ash, and from Ruby as well.

00:53:34.200 --> 00:53:35.400
SPEAKER: Thanks for coming.

00:53:35.400 --> 00:53:37.250
GELONG THUBTEN: Thank you.

